SIMPLE: idealism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Idealism
<hw>I*de"al*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>id⟦eacute⟧alisme</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or
state of being ideal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Conception of the ideal; imagery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>The system or theory that
denies the existence of material bodies, and teaches that we have no
rational grounds to believe in the reality of anything but ideas and
their relations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The practice or habit of giving or attributing ideal
form or character to things; treatment of things in art or literature
according to ideal standards or patterns; -- opposed to
<contr>realism</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>a belief in the feasibility of the implementation of
ideal principles and noble goals, and the practice or habit of pursuing
such goals; -- opposed to <contr>realism</contr> and
<contr>cynicism</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Idealist</ent>⟦br⟧
